            	<h3>General Rule</h3>
            	<p><strong>
            		selector {<br>
            		....property: value;<br>
            		....anotherProperty: value;<br>
            		}</strong>
            		<ul>
            			<li>
            				Selector
            				<ul>
            					<li>The HTML element name at the stare of the set of rules that will be applied to the HTML element selected. The "selector" identifies the element(s) to by styled.</li>
            				</ul>
            			</li>
            			<li>
            				Declaration
            				<ul>
            					<li>
            						A single rule, like color: red;, specifying which of the elements' properties you want to style
            					</li>
            				</ul>
            			</li>
            			<li>
            				Properties
            				<ul>
            					<li>
            						Ways in which you can style an HTML element, or, the name of whichever one of the myriad of different styling options that can be applied to an HTML element.
            					</li>
            				</ul>
            			</li>
            			<li>
            				Property Value
            				<ul>
            					<li>
            						To the right of the property (after the color) is the "value" that will be applied to the specific property of the HTML element being styled. Ex: if the property of an H1 element is "color:", then a potential value could be "red;".
            						Thus:<br><strong>
            						h1 {<br>
            						....color: red;<br>
            						}<br></strong>
            					</li>
            				</ul>
            			</li>
            			<li>
            				Additionally:
            				<ul>
            					<li>
            						Each "rule set" must be wrapped in curly braces {}. A "rule set" is the declaration of the value of a property, and it's called a "rule set" because declaration changes the rules of how the HTML element would be displayed to the screen since. The default HTML styling is horrendous and meant for structuring nothing but academic articles, thus, imposing new rules onto how the default will style means that you can tell the webpage what the default styling is going to be. This "telling the webpage what the default styling is going to be" is the same as saying that you will tell the webpge how to style all of the HTML elements. The way to do this is by imposing rules  
            					</li>
            					<li>
            						Separate property from value with a :. Example: example 
            					</li>
            					<li>
            						Separate declarations (rule sets) from one another (the individual lines of styling within a selector) by ending each declaration with a ;
            						Example: example;
            					</li>
            				</ul>
            			</li>
            			<li>
            				Multiple elements can be selected at once, for example:<br><strong>
            				p, li, h1 {<br>
            				....color: red;<br>
            				}<br></strong>
            			</li>
            		</ul>
            	</p>
            	<h3>Write CSS in a separate file from the main HTML document</h3>
